==Death, burial and fate of remains==
[[File:Alfred the Great's will.jpg|thumb|upright|Alfred's will]]
Alfred died on 26 October 899.{{sfn|Blair|1977|page=80}} How he died is unknown, although he suffered throughout his life with a painful and unpleasant illness. His biographer Asser gave a detailed description of Alfred's symptoms and this has allowed modern doctors to provide a possible diagnosis. It is thought that he had either [[Crohn's disease]] or [[hemorrhoids|haemorrhoidal disease]].{{sfn|Craig|1991|pp=303–05}}{{sfn|Jackson|1992|p=58}} His grandson King [[Eadred]] seems to have suffered from a similar illness.{{sfn|Malmesbury|1904|p=145}}{{efn|According to St Dunstan's apprentice "...poor King Eadred would suck the juice out of the food, chew what remained for a little while and spit it out: a nasty practice that often turned the stomachs of the thegns who dined with him."{{sfn|Dunstan|1992|p=248}}}}

Alfred was originally buried temporarily in the [[Old Minster, Winchester|Old Minster]] in [[Winchester]]. Four years after his death he was moved to the [[New Minster, Winchester|New Minster]] (perhaps built especially to receive his body). When the New Minster moved to Hyde, a little north of the city, in 1110, the monks were transferred to [[Hyde Abbey]] along with Alfred's body and those of his wife and children, which were presumably interred before the high altar. Soon after the dissolution of the abbey in 1539, during the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], the church was demolished, leaving the graves intact.{{sfn|Winchester Museums Service|2009|loc=Hyde Community Archaeology Project}}

The royal graves and many others were probably rediscovered by chance in 1788 when a prison was being constructed by convicts on the site. Prisoners dug across the width of the altar area in order to dispose of rubble left at the dissolution. Coffins were stripped of lead, and bones were scattered and lost. The prison was demolished between 1846 and 1850.{{sfn|The Church Monuments Society|2014}} Further excavations in 1866 and 1897 were inconclusive.{{sfn|Winchester Museums Service|2009|loc=Hyde Community Archaeology Project}}{{sfn|Dodson|2004|p=37}} In 1866, amateur antiquarian John Mellor claimed to have recovered a number of bones from the site which he said were those of Alfred. These later came into the possession of the vicar of nearby St Bartholomew's Church who reburied them in an unmarked grave in the church graveyard.{{sfn|The Church Monuments Society|2014}}

Excavations conducted by the Winchester Museums Service of the Hyde Abbey site in 1999 located a second pit dug in front of where the high altar would have been located, which was identified as probably dating to Mellor's 1886 excavation.{{sfn|Winchester Museums Service|2009|loc=Hyde Community Archaeology Project}} The 1999 archeological excavation uncovered the foundations of the abbey buildings and some bones. Bones suggested at the time to be those of Alfred proved instead to belong to an elderly woman.{{sfn|Kennedy|2013}}

In March 2013, the Diocese of Winchester [[exhume]]d the bones from the unmarked grave at St Bartholomew's and placed them in secure storage. The diocese made no claim they were the bones of Alfred, but intended to secure them for later analysis, and from the attentions of people whose interest may have been sparked by the recent identification of the remains of [[Richard III of England|King Richard III]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2013}}{{sfn|Cohen|2013}} The bones were [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon-dated]] but the results showed that they were from the 1300s and therefore not of Alfred.

In January 2014, a fragment of [[pelvis]] unearthed in the 1999 excavation of the Hyde site, which had subsequently lain in a Winchester museum store room, was radiocarbon-dated to the correct period. It has been suggested that this bone may belong to either Alfred or his son [[Edward the Elder|Edward]], but this remains unproven.{{sfn|BBC staff|2014}}{{sfn|Keys|2014}}

==Legacy==
{{see also|Cultural depictions of Alfred the Great}}
[[File:Statue of King Alfred in Wantage Market Square.jpg|thumb|upright|Statue of Alfred the Great at [[Wantage]], Oxfordshire]]

Alfred is venerated as a [[saint]] by some Christian traditions,<ref name="cathsaints">{{cite web|title=Saint Alfred the Great|url=https://catholicsaints.info/saint-alfred-the-great/|website=CatholicSaints.info|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref> An attempt by [[Henry VI of England]] in 1441 to have him canonized by the [[Pope Eugene IV|pope]] was unsuccessful but he is venerated in the Catholic Church.{{sfn|Foot|2011|p=231}}{{efn|Some [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] Christians believe that Alfred should be recognised as a saint. See [http://www.orthodoxengland.org.uk/athlifea.htm Case for] and [http://sarisburium.blogspot.com/2008/11/king-alfred-of-england-orthodox-saint.html Case against]}} The [[Anglican Communion]] venerates him as a [[Saints in Anglicanism|Christian hero]], with a [[Lesser Festival (Anglicanism)|feast day]] or commemoration on 26 October, and he may often be found depicted in [[stained glass]] in [[Church of England parish church]]es.{{sfn|Horspool|2006|pp=190–91}}

Alfred commissioned Bishop Asser to write his biography, which inevitably emphasised Alfred's positive aspects. Later medieval historians, such as [[Geoffrey of Monmouth]], also reinforced Alfred's favourable image. By the time of the [[Reformation]] Alfred was seen as being a pious Christian ruler who promoted the use of English rather than Latin, and so the translations that he commissioned were viewed as untainted by the later Roman Catholic influences of the Normans. Consequently, it was writers of the sixteenth century who gave Alfred his epithet as 'the Great' rather than any of Alfred's contemporaries.{{sfn|Yorke|1999}} The epithet was retained by succeeding generations of Parliamentarians and empire-builders who saw Alfred's patriotism, success against barbarism, promotion of education and establishment of the rule of law as supporting their own ideals.{{sfn|Yorke|1999}}

A number of educational establishments are named in Alfred's honour. These include:
*The [[University of Winchester]] created from the former 'King Alfred's College, Winchester' (1928 to 2004).
*[[Alfred University]] and [[Alfred State College]] in [[Alfred (village), New York|Alfred, New York]]. The local telephone exchange for Alfred University is 871 in commemoration of Alfred's ascension to the throne.
*In honour of Alfred, the [[University of Liverpool]] created a [[King Alfred Chair of English Literature]].
[[File:Alfred the Great - Samuel Woodforde.jpg|thumb|upright|18th century portrait of Alfred by [[Samuel Woodforde]]]]
*[[King Alfred's Academy]], a secondary school in [[Wantage]], [[Oxfordshire]], the birthplace of Alfred.
*King's Lodge School in [[Chippenham, Wiltshire]] is so named because King Alfred's hunting lodge is reputed to have stood on or near the site of the school.
*The King Alfred School & Specialist Sports Academy, Burnham Road, Highbridge is so named due to its rough proximity to Brent Knoll (a Beacon site) and Athelney.
*The King Alfred School in Barnet, North London, UK.
*King Alfred's Middle School, [[Shaftesbury]], [[Dorset]] [Now defunct after reorganisation]
*[[King's College, Taunton]], Somerset. (The king in question is King Alfred).
*King Alfred's house in [[Bishop Stopford's School at Enfield]].
*Saxonwold Primary School in Gauteng, South Africa names one of its houses after King Alfred. The others being Bede, Caedmon, and Dunston.

The [[Royal Navy]] has named one ship and two [[shore establishment]]s [[HMS King Alfred|HMS ''King Alfred'']], and one of the first ships of the [[United States Navy|US Navy]] was named [[USS Alfred|USS ''Alfred'']] in his honour. In 2002, Alfred was ranked number 14 in the [[BBC]]'s list of the [[100 Greatest Britons]] following a UK-wide vote.{{sfn|Daily Mail staff|2002}}

==Statues==
===Alfred University (New York)===
One of the first items visible when entering the campus of Alfred University is a bronze statue of the king, created in 1990 by William Underhill. It features the king as a young man, holding a shield in his left hand and an open book in his right.<ref>Alfred University : About AU : Statue of King Alfred, Alfred University, www.alfred.edu/glance/statue_of_king_alfred.cfm.</ref>

===Pewsey===
A prominent statue of King Alfred the Great stands in the middle of [[Pewsey]]. It was unveiled in June 1913 to commemorate the coronation of King [[George V]].<ref>[http://www.pewsey-uk.co.uk/pewsey-village-history.html Pewsey.uk website: Village History]</ref>

===Wantage===
A statue of Alfred the Great, situated in the [[Wantage]] [[market place]], was sculpted by [[Prince Victor of Hohenlohe-Langenburg|Count Gleichen]], a relative of [[Queen Victoria]], and unveiled on 14 July 1877 by the [[Edward VII|Prince]] and [[Alexandra of Denmark|Princess of Wales]].{{sfn|Townsend|2008}}
The statue was vandalised on [[New Year's Eve]] 2007, losing part of its right arm and axe. After the arm and axe were replaced the statue was again vandalised on [[Christmas Eve]] 2008, losing its axe.{{sfn|Townsend|2008}}

===Winchester===
A bronze statue of Alfred the Great stands at the eastern end of The Broadway, close to the site of [[Winchester]]'s medieval East Gate. The statue was designed by [[Hamo Thornycroft]], and erected in 1899 to mark one thousand years since Alfred's death.<ref>David Ross, [http://www.britainexpress.com/counties/hampshire/winchester/alfred-statue.htm Statue of King Alfred the Great] BritainExpress. Retrieved 3 October 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.visitwinchester.co.uk/king-alfred-great Visit Winchester: King Alfred the Great]</ref> The statue is placed on a pedestal consisting of two immense blocks of grey Cornish granite.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/thornycroft/36.html Victorian Web: Alfred the Great - Sculpture by Sir W. Hamo Thornycroft]</ref>

===Cleveland, Ohio===
A marble statue of Alfred the Great stands on the North side of the [[Cuyahoga County Courthouse]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]]. It was sculpted by Isidore Konti in 1910.<ref>[http://oosi.sculpturecenter.org/items/show/345 "Alfred the Great", Isidore Konti 1910"]. Sculpture Center. Retrieved 3 October 2017.</ref>

