In [[music]], the '''''pianto''''' (en:crying) is the [[motif (music)|motif]] of a descending [[semitone|minor second]], has represented [[lament]]s and been associated [[lyrics|textually]] with [[crying|weeping]], [[sigh|sighing]] (called the '''Mannheim sigh''' by [[Hugo Riemann]]); or pain, grief, etc.; since the 16th century.<ref name="Monelle">Monelle, Raymond (2000). ''The Sense of Music: Semiotic Essays'', p.17. {{ISBN|978-0-691-05716-3}}.</ref> For example the ''[[chromatic fourth|passus duriusculus]]''.<ref name="Monelle"/> "It was present equally in [[vocal music|vocal]] and [[instrumental]] music."<ref name="Monelle"/>

